Headlines.Headline: Dover Corp To Issue $600M Of 10-Year, 30-Year Notes

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Dover Corp.

will issue two classes of interest-bearing notes, for an aggregate of $600 million, to repay borrowings under its commercial-paper program. The New York-based industrial manufacturing holding company will issue $350 million of 5.45% notes due 2018 and $250 million of 6.6% notes due 2038, with the transaction expected to close Friday. #text:
An overwhelming 95 percent of American investors expressed
    satisfaction with the return on their mutual fund investments, according to a recent
    survey. The ten year bull stampede may have made these investors insensitive to risk,
    however. Only two in five investors recall ever seeing the required warning that
    "past mutual fund performance is no guarantee of future return," said
, chairman of pollster

. He
    believes that investors are convinced that funds have "built-in safety factors"
    and that impressive rates will continue to grow. The fund companies have done "a
    superb job of eliminating fears that investor dollars are at serious risk." Further,
    a slim majority of mutual fund investors (61.6 percent) say they actually read the
    prospectus before buying shares.

Headlines.Headline: Seagate misses forecasts

#text: Seagate Technology Inc. (SEG)

traded higher Tuesday after reporting a substantial third-quarter loss and continued weak
    industry conditions. The disk drive maker posted a loss of 10 cents a share excluding a
    43-cent restructuring charge. Analysts had expected a loss of 9 cents a share. Sales
    decreased to $1.7 billion from $2.5 billion a year ago. The company cited falling
    disk-drive prices and weak demand for the loss. Shares closed up 1 11/16 to 26 1/2 ahead
    of the report, but rose 3 3/16 to 28 in after-hours trading.
